rance,":"Surgères, Charente-Maritime, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Tusson,16390,Charente,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,France,":"Tusson, Charente, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Gençay,86103,Vienne,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Gençay, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Jeanne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of   Jean ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jeanne Maingot de Surgères was born about 1173, in Surgères, Charente-Maritime, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. She married Geoffroi V de RANCON on 5 September 1217, in Surgères, Charente-Maritime, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 1235, in Tusson, Charente, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France, at the age of 64."},"et":{"ABT 1173–ABT 1235":"umbes 1173–umbes 1235","1175–1258":"1175–1258","1206–1269":"1206–1269","1173–1235":"1173–1235","1206":"1206","ABT 1173":"umbes 1173","1269":"1269","1258":"1258","1235":"1235","ABT 1235":"umbes 1235","1175":"1175","5 SEP 1217":"5. september 1217","1173":"1173","ABT 1206":"umbes 1206","Surgères,17434,Charente-Maritime,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,France,":"Surgères, Charente-Maritime, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Tusson,16390,Charente,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,France,":"Tusson, Charente, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Gençay,86103,Vienne,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Gençay, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1173–ABT 1235":"noin 1173–noin 1235","1175–1258":"1175–1258","1206–1269":"1206–1269","1173–1235":"1173–1235","1206":"1206","ABT 1173":"noin 1173","1269":"1269","1258":"1258","1235":"1235","ABT 1235":"noin 1235","1175":"1175","5 SEP 1217":"5. syyskuuta 1217","1173":"1173","ABT 1206":"noin 1206","Surgères,17434,Charente-Maritime,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,France,":"Surgères, Charente-Maritime, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska","Tusson,16390,Chare